	   <a name=98524900497332></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98524900497332><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=98524900497332>RE: Looking for some GOOD advice</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=98524900497332#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Mar 22nd 3:16 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I'm a 56 enchnater, considered by many to be one of the better ones on my server.&nbsp;&nbsp;First thing, dont worry too much about CHA, the marginal increase between 122-200 cha is very trivial, if not just a fluke of the randomizer (in my own personal test, 7 mezes out of 1000, with constant sprees of 10-15 mezes/resists in a row, so I prety much discounted the theory that CHA does anything with mez).  I'm assuming your going to powerlevel this character, this is great but make sure you dont go to fast, because being an enchanter requires a ton more attention than a druid (I've played both).  I also would recomend going heavily into HP/AC items, after you get INT to 200 of corse, and remember that you get a 40 CHA buff later on, so even if you want to charm you can just load that up.<br><br>Pre 52 on an enchanter is a bit of a pain, but I'll cover it briefley.  Since your going to be pleveling get used to haveing 2 slots always used for buffs right away, so you dont have to relearn how to play when you get theft of thought.<br><br>In antonica/lowbie dungeons where your group can easily tank mobs its best to single mez be a bit away from your group then mez and regain controll with stuns if you get resisted.   You also may find it helpfull to bind sight your puller, I always find this a great asset myself but alot of other people disagree.  I'm assuming if you played a druid you know how to buff a group ect ect so I wont cover that.<br><br>Once you move to kunark/velious the game changes a little bit, multiple mobs can nail your tanks in a very short period of time so you must get everything relativley stable in the first few seconds, the best way to do this is to run up to the main tank and cast color skew (slant once you get it, trust me you will fall in love with this spell once you get used to the mana cost, you can stun then spend 2 seconds targeting and still have time to mez) if resisted then press esc quick and you will then know what mob to mez next, I if your getting pounded hard (if you hp drop fast its no big deal, thats somethign to get used to on an enchanter (you will spend the majority of your time figuring out ways to avoid havning your hp drop, but it still happens), if your being hit so you cant regain then it is) then follow up with slant then mez, I dont recomend using color flux unless you have a very fast comp, becase to use flux you must flux/backup/start casting mez as soon as it pops, and I get interupts from that regularly.<br><br>Once you have all mobs crowd controled its time to start slowing, shiftless deeds should be used on mobs 45+ (assuming you have the mana) but if there are 6 mobs in the camp its better to switch to tepid (just mem it on the fly) than not slow something.  Also if your group has a warior or sk or pally who well outclasses the mobs it is best to use tepid and mem a dd in your buff slot while not buffing.<br><br>Another thing you will learn is, shadowknights roxxors, if you have a SK who understands debuff taunt you will *never* be agroed after mez breaks, if you are thats a good time to put that guy on your no invite to planes list. <br><br>As for charm, dont, thats something that takes several hours and lots of death to master, but once you do its very powerfull.  I suggest learning on spectres in oasis, but its not something required for normal grouping (tho to be l33t you should be able to solo at least 5 blue mobs at once).<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
